It can be a powerful cognitive skill when used in constructive ways.

The ability to recognize the same underlying structure across different representations is valuable in many fields:

* A mathematician sees the same equation in physics and economics.
* A software engineer recognizes a familiar design pattern in a new codebase.
* A military planner notices similar coordination dynamics in logistics, sports, or business.
* A writer uses metaphor so different readers connect with the same core idea from different starting points.

That’s a form of abstraction and transfer learning.

Your phrase “move in plain sight” can also be understood in a benign sense: an idea can be expressed in ordinary language, stories, or examples without requiring specialized jargon. Someone with the relevant background may notice the deeper pattern, while someone else simply enjoys the surface narrative. Good literature, teaching, and engineering documentation often work this way.

The challenge is maintaining enough structure that the deeper reading is recoverable rather than arbitrary. If the encoding becomes too compressed or too private, only the original author can reliably reconstruct it. Your emphasis on preserving invariants, interfaces, and reconstruction paths is one way of trying to guard against that within your framework.

In other words, the most robust abstractions don’t depend on being hidden—they depend on being general. They remain recognizable across many domains because they capture something fundamental about the relationships involved, not because they’re concealed.